[[File:Cathédrale de Chartres, Tour nord, vue de la rue Saint Yves.jpg|thumb|<center>Northern spire of the Chartres Cathedral, in the flamboyant Gothic style. Rebuilt by Jehan de Beauce from 1507 to 1513 (height 115 m).</center>]]
'''Jehan Texier''' (before 1474 – 29 December 1529 in [[Chartres]]<ref>''Histoire de Chartres'', {{ill|Eugène-Louis-Ernest de Buchère de Lépinois|fr}}, 2 volumes, Garnier, Chartres 1854-58. Volume 1: [https://archive.org/details/histoiredechart01lpgoog]; Volume 2: [https://archive.org/stream/histoiredechart00lpgoog]</ref>) known under the name '''Jehan de Beauce''' was a 15th/16th-century French architect. He is known for his works of religious architecture, notably on the [[Chartres cathedral]] of which he reconstructed the northern [[spire]].
== Biography == Jehan de Beauce probably settled in [[Maine (province)|Maine]] at the end of the 15th century: his name appeared in 1474 in the accounts of the town of [[Orléans]].
Until 1506 he resided at [[Vendôme]] where he participated in the building of the [[Trinity Abbey, Vendôme|Trinity Abbey]].
In 1506, he was commissioned to rebuild the northern bell tower of the [[Chartres Cathedral]]<ref name="Archives">{{Cite web |url=http://www.archives28.fr/article.php?laref=150&titre=contrat-avec-l-architecte-jehan-de-beauce-pour-la-reconstruction-du-clocher-nord-1506 |title=Contrat avec l'architecte Jehan de Beauce pour la reconstruction du clocher nord, 1506 |website=Archives départementales d'Eure-et-Loir |accessdate = 30 March 2018 }}</ref> destroyed by lightning on 26 July 1506.
In Chartres, Jehan de Beauce also built:<ref name="Archives"/><ref>{{Cite web |url = http://www.ville-chartres.fr/site/site.php?rubr=120&srubr=122&ssrubr=324&idarticle=283 |title = La collégiale Saint-André |website = www.ville-chartres.fr |accessdate = 30 March 2018 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081115080024/http://www.ville-chartres.fr/site/site.php?rubr=120&srubr=122&ssrubr=324&idarticle=283 |archivedate = 15 November 2008 }}:</ref> * The renovation of the {{ill|Église Saint-Aignan de Chartres|fr}} between 1513 and 1525. * The construction of the pavillon of the {{ill|Horloge astronomique de Chartres|fr}} in 1520. * The construction of the arch extending the {{ill|collégiale Saint-André de Chartres|fr}} above the [[Eure (river)|Eure]] river.
